  "notes": "Two logs for the same hole. Pp.1-5 = the detailed geologist's log (rich verbatim: fossils, seam names with letter codes, named marine bands); pp.6-7 = a cleaner borer's-journal summary with plainer names (Soil/Sand/Fireclay/Band) but per-bed Thickness AND Depth. This record follows the RICHER geologist's log (pp.1-5) for verbatim, classification, depths and seam names. The geologist's log leaves most THICKNESS cells blank (a few coals are written, and several beds are brace-grouped with a combined figure), while its DEPTH column is complete and reliable; thickness_ffi here is therefore DERIVED as depth[i]-depth[i-1]. Where the geologist did write a coal thickness it matches the derivation (Low Main 3-2, Top Hutton 2-1, Harvey 2-0, K1/L2/P groups), and the borer's-journal per-bed thicknesses independently corroborate. The two copies subdivide the strata slightly differently below 60 ft (e.g. geologist splits Grey shale + Mudstone where the borer lumps two grey-shale beds; base of Low Main seatearth 177-8 vs 177-0), but they agree at every major seam depth (Low Main 176-8, Brass Thill 205-206, Hutton 255-6/270-271, Harvey 396-6, Tilley 434-435) and both end at 450 ft. Final depth 450 ft 0 in = 137.16 m, matching the index. Header: cored from 60 ft; base of unconsolidated deposits at 57 ft; open hole above. Commenced 3/12/57, completed 14/1/58; borer Cementation Co. PENCIL MARGINALIA (later BGS seam correlations, in the notes column of the borer's-journal copy, p.7) recorded verbatim on the corresponding intervals and in seam_marks: '? PLESSEY' by the 282 ft coal (int.46), '? B.PL' by the 302 ft coal (int.56), '? R. PLESSEY' by the 322 ft coal (int.61), 'AMB' by the 364-11 coal below Harvey Marine Band (int.75), and '4.Bd. Beaumont' beside HARVEY (N) (int.90). A pencil line across the p.6 header reads 'This hole re-numbered by ... NZ 24 SE ...' (administrative). Faint illegible pencil also present in the p.6 notes column; not transcribable. Blue BGS banner, watermarks and registration stamps ignored per instructions. Half-inch measurements occur in the Tilley coal group (int.106 thickness 0-0-9.5 to depth 434-1.5; int.107 0-0-2.5)."
